        'content'   => '<!-- wp:snel/content-section {"contentTranslations":{"en":["\\u003cp\\u003eEvery business needs marketing. Almost no entrepreneur wants to do it.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eThat\'s normal. Marketing takes time, energy, and creativity — and you don\'t see the results right away. So most entrepreneurs push it aside.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eAI has changed that. You can now create content in a few hours that used to take half a day. And with automation, you can let that system run by itself.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eBut this is where it goes wrong.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eMost entrepreneurs automate a system that doesn\'t work. And automating something bad only makes it worse, faster.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eIn this article, I will explain which system I use — and why strategy always comes before automation.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch2 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eThe mistake almost everyone makes\\u003c/h2\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eYou install an AI tool. You ask for a few posts. You schedule them. Done.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eBut no one reads it.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eThe problem isn\'t automation. The problem is the input. Generic content — top 10 tips, general advice, smooth AI prose — is no longer read. Not on Twitter, not on Instagram, not on a blog.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eThere are hundreds of thousands of people sharing the same \\u0022top 10 tips.\\u0022 If you don\'t add anything that only you can say, why would anyone read you?\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eThe only thing you have that AI doesn\'t is your own experiences, stories, and opinions. That\'s the foundation. Only then does automation make sense.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch2 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eTwo systems that work\\u003c/h2\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eI use two systems for content. Both start with long-form. That\'s the foundation.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch3 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eSystem 1: start with video\\u003c/h3\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eYou create a long YouTube video — at least five minutes, preferably ten or more.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eFrom that video:\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cul class=\\u0022wp-block-list\\u0022\\u003e \\u003cli\\u003eyou clip short Reels and Shorts\\u003c/li\\u003e \\u003cli\\u003eyou extract the transcript\\u003c/li\\u003e \\u003cli\\u003eyou turn that transcript into a blog post\\u003c/li\\u003e \\u003cli\\u003efrom the blog post, you generate Twitter posts, threads, and Instagram posts via AI\\u003c/li\\u003e \\u003c/ul\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eYouTube and blogs are evergreen. They continue to attract traffic, even a year later. A Reel peaks for three days and then disappears. Not YouTube.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch3 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eSystem 2: start with writing\\u003c/h3\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eYou first write a blog post. Not fully AI-generated — you write the outline, you add your own stories and examples. AI helps with elaboration, not ideation.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eFrom that blog post:\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cul class=\\u0022wp-block-list\\u0022\\u003e \\u003cli\\u003eyou record a YouTube video (the post is your script)\\u003c/li\\u003e \\u003cli\\u003eyou create clips and Reels from the video\\u003c/li\\u003e \\u003cli\\u003eyou generate Twitter and Instagram posts via AI\\u003c/li\\u003e \\u003c/ul\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eThis is my preference. Everything starts with the blog. One piece of content produces multiple formats.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch2 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eWhy long-form is the core\\u003c/h2\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eShort-form does not build trust.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eNo one buys anything from you based on 180 characters. But when someone reads a good article from you, they start to know you. And people buy from people they know.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eI always refer back to an article or video in all my social posts. Never the other way around. The blog is the centerpiece, the posts are the signposts.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch2 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eThe swipe file — the piece that people skip\\u003c/h2\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eIf you let AI write Twitter posts without further instruction, they all sound the same. Generic. Forgettable.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eWhat does work: building a database of posts that already perform. Don\'t copy the text, but the structure. Every good tweet has a structure — a hook, a body, a conclusion. You can repeat that structure with different content.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eI built that database on Twitter and Threads for three years. AI takes those structures and applies them to new content. That sounds like me, not a robot.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eWithout a swipe file, everything AI writes sounds the same. Then you don\'t want to automate that.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch2 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eHow I do it\\u003c/h2\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eI built Repurposa — a WordPress plugin that automates this entire system.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eCreate a blog post, repurpose it to Twitter, Threads, and Instagram posts, schedule on all platforms — all in one interface. On your own WordPress website, so your SEO, your traffic, your data.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eWant to set it up without an interface? Claude Code plus the right APIs is enough. A bit more manual work, but it works.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003ch2 class=\\u0022wp-block-heading\\u0022\\u003eWhat you take away\\u003c/h2\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eStrategy first. Automation later.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eYour own stories are the only thing no one can copy. Build your content around that. Use long-form as the basis and let AI recycle the rest.\\u003c/p\\u003e","\\u003cp\\u003eInterested in Repurposa or want me to set up a content system for your business? Send a m